The sshd server, and file transfer.

We've been on the client side; now let's look at the server. The sshd daemon is what listens on port twenty-two and handles incoming connections, and its configuration lives in etc-ssh-slash-sshd-underscore-config. A handful of settings are the ones you'll actually touch. PermitRootLogin, set to prohibit-password, lets root log in only with a key, never a password, or you can set it to no to forbid root SSH entirely, which is more secure. PasswordAuthentication no rejects password attempts altogether, requiring keys. And AllowUsers, with a list of names, whitelists exactly who is permitted to log in.

Now the single most important operational habit in this section: after editing the config, always validate it and reload before you disconnect. Here's why. If you reload with a broken config, your current session stays alive, but new connections will fail, and if you've already logged out, you are now locked out. So the drill is: run sudo sshd dash-t, which does a syntax check and stays silent if everything's fine. Then sudo systemctl reload sshd to apply it. Then, crucially, keep your current session open and open a second, brand-new SSH session to confirm it actually works. Only once that second session succeeds do you close the first. For production hardening, the checklist is: disable password authentication, restrict or disable root login, firewall port twenty-two, add something like fail2ban to ban repeat offenders, and watch the auth log.

The other half of this section is moving files, and both tools here run over SSH, so they inherit all of SSH's authentication and encryption for free. The first is scp, secure copy, which is basically cp that works across machines. One gotcha: for a custom port, scp uses capital dash-P, unlike ssh's lowercase dash-p. scp is fine for a file or two. But for anything serious, use rsync. rsync is incremental, it only transfers the files, and even the bytes, that actually changed; it's resumable; and it's ideal for backups. The typical invocation is rsync dash-a-v-z, where dash-a is archive mode, preserving permissions and timestamps, dash-v is verbose, and dash-z compresses in transit. Add dash-dash-delete to make the destination a true mirror of the source.

And finally, the rsync gotcha that ruins backups: the trailing slash. A source path ending in a slash means "copy the contents of this directory." Without the trailing slash, you copy the directory itself, creating an extra level of nesting at the destination. Always stop and think about which one you actually want.
